<?php
$ethicsOptions = array("a" => "Informed consent", "b" => "Privacy", "c" => "Confidentiality", "d" => "Anonymity", "e" => "Data minimization", "f" => "Debriefing", "g" => "Research integrity");

return array(
    "overview" => "Statistical power does not outweigh human responsibility. Ethical research protects choice, limits risk, secures information, reports honestly, and considers how biased data or misleading displays may harm people and communities.",
    "objectives" => array("Evaluate informed consent, assent, voluntariness, risk, benefit, and the right to withdraw.", "Distinguish privacy, confidentiality, and anonymity.", "Explain data minimization, security, deception, debriefing, and institutional review.", "Identify fabrication, falsification, selective reporting, p-hacking, and misleading visualization.", "Evaluate dataset fairness and write an ethical review of a proposed study."),
    "prerequisites" => array("Recognize sampling bias and misleading graphs.", "Understand experiments, treatments, and data collection.", "Explain study limitations in context."),
    "vocabulary" => array(
        array("Informed consent", "Voluntary agreement after understandable information about procedures, risks, benefits, data use, and withdrawal."),
        array("Assent", "A minor's affirmative agreement to participate, alongside required guardian permission."),
        array("Privacy", "A person's control over access to themselves and their information."),
        array("Confidentiality", "Researchers can identify participants but protect identities from disclosure."),
        array("Anonymity", "Responses are not reasonably linked to participant identities, including by the research team."),
        array("Data minimization", "Collecting only information reasonably necessary for the research purpose."),
        array("Deception", "Withholding or misrepresenting information when justified, minimal-risk, reviewed, and followed by debriefing."),
        array("Debriefing", "Explaining the true purpose and relevant procedures after participation."),
        array("Fabrication", "Inventing data or observations."),
        array("Falsification", "Dishonestly manipulating methods, materials, or data.")
    ),
    "sections" => array(
        array("title" => "Respectful and Voluntary Participation", "content" => array(
            "<p><strong>Informed consent</strong> is a process, not merely a signature. Participants should receive understandable information about the study's purpose, what they will do, foreseeable risks and benefits, how data will be used, whether participation is voluntary, and how to stop. Important details should not be hidden in language that a participant cannot reasonably understand.</p>",
            "<p>Consent obtained through pressure is not genuinely voluntary. A teacher, employer, coach, or authority figure must take special care because people may fear consequences. Rewards may compensate time, but an extremely large reward can create undue influence for economically vulnerable people. Refusing or withdrawing should not bring inappropriate punishment.</p>",
            "<p>Research involving minors may require permission from a parent or guardian and <strong>assent</strong> from the young person. Assent means the minor affirmatively agrees at an age-appropriate level; silence is not enough. Requirements vary by school, organization, and jurisdiction, so a classroom activity should follow local policy without pretending to be a professional medical trial.</p>",
            array("type" => "warning", "label" => "Consent does not excuse avoidable harm", "html" => "<p>Researchers still have a duty to minimize risk. A participant cannot make reckless design or unnecessary data collection ethical merely by signing a form.</p>")
        )),
        array("title" => "Privacy, Confidentiality, and Anonymity", "content" => array(
            "<p><strong>Privacy</strong> concerns whether and how researchers access a person or their information. Observing students in a setting where they reasonably expect privacy is different from using public aggregate records. Researchers should avoid unnecessary intrusion and explain any observation or record linkage.</p>",
            "<p><strong>Confidentiality</strong> means researchers know or can link identities but promise to protect them. Names may be stored separately from responses, access may be restricted, and reports may use grouped results. <strong>Anonymity</strong> is stronger: identities are not collected or cannot reasonably be connected to responses. A survey that collects email addresses is confidential at best, not anonymous.</p>",
            "<p>Removing names does not always create anonymity. A combination of school, grade, rare medical condition, and exact age might identify a person. Reports about small groups should suppress or combine details when re-identification is plausible. Researchers must state honestly what protections they can provide and any limits to confidentiality.</p>",
            array("type" => "definition", "label" => "Quick distinction", "html" => "<p>Privacy asks whether access is appropriate. Confidentiality asks how known identities are protected. Anonymity means the data are not reasonably linked to identity.</p>")
        )),
        array("title" => "Collect Less, Protect More", "content" => array(
            "<p><strong>Data minimization</strong> means collecting only what is needed. A homework-completion study may need assignment records and grade level but not a home address, personal contacts, or exact birth date. Unused sensitive fields create risk without improving the answer. Retention periods should also be limited: data should not be kept forever by default.</p>",
            "<p>Conceptual data-security protections include restricted access, strong authentication, encrypted storage and transfer, separation of identity keys from study data, removal of identifiers, secure backups, and safe deletion. A written plan should identify who can access raw data, why, for how long, and what happens if a breach occurs.</p>",
            "<p>Risk includes more than physical harm. Emotional distress, embarrassment, academic consequences, financial loss, discrimination, social conflict, and privacy exposure all matter. Vulnerable populations may need extra protection because power differences or limited decision-making capacity can weaken voluntariness. Benefits should be realistic rather than exaggerated to recruit participation.</p>"
        )),
        array("title" => "Deception, Oversight, and Debriefing", "content" => array(
            "<p>Sometimes revealing a study's exact purpose would change behaviour. Limited <strong>deception</strong> may be considered only when the question is important, alternatives are inadequate, risk is minimal, independent oversight approves the plan, and participants are later debriefed. Researchers should not deceive participants about serious risks or use deception merely because honest recruitment is inconvenient.</p>",
            "<p><strong>Debriefing</strong> explains the true purpose, what information was withheld, why it was necessary, and how participants can ask questions or withdraw data when appropriate. Debriefing also helps repair misunderstanding and provides support if the procedure caused concern.</p>",
            "<p>Institutional review boards, or IRBs, review formal human-participant research. They evaluate risk, consent, recruitment, privacy, and safeguards. Not every ordinary classroom survey follows the same process as a medical trial, but school and organization policies still apply. When uncertain, researchers should seek responsible adult, institutional, or ethics guidance before collecting data.</p>",
            array("type" => "note", "label" => "Independent review", "html" => "<p>Researchers can be excited about their own project and underestimate risk. Independent review adds perspectives and makes safeguards explicit.</p>")
        )),
        array("title" => "Integrity, Fairness, and Honest Communication", "content" => array(
            "<p><strong>Fabrication</strong> invents data. <strong>Falsification</strong> manipulates procedures or data dishonestly. <strong>Selective reporting</strong> hides relevant unfavourable results while displaying only favourable outcomes. <strong>P-hacking</strong> informally describes trying many analyses or exclusions until something appears statistically impressive, then reporting it as if it were the original plan. These practices make evidence unreliable and betray participants who contributed data.</p>",
            "<p>Visual displays carry ethical duties. Truncated axes, unequal intervals, missing categories, selective dates, inconsistent scales, and three-dimensional decoration can exaggerate or hide differences. A technically accurate number can still be presented deceptively. Labels, scales, sources, uncertainty, and relevant context should be visible.</p>",
            "<p>Datasets may encode historical or sampling inequities. A prediction system trained mostly on one group may perform poorly for others. Fairness review asks who is represented, how labels were created, which errors matter for each group, and who bears harm. Adding more data from the same narrow source does not solve representation.</p>",
            "<p>Ethical reporting includes limitations, missing data, all planned outcomes, conflicts of interest, and corrections. A negative or uncertain result is still information. The goal of statistics is not to produce a desired answer; it is to make uncertainty and evidence clearer.</p>"
        ))
    ),
    "worked_examples" => array(
        array("title" => "Named wellbeing survey", "scenario" => "Students must submit a named mental-health survey or lose participation marks.", "steps" => array("The grade penalty makes participation coercive rather than voluntary.", "Names attached to sensitive responses create substantial confidentiality risk.", "Collect only necessary information, use an independent voluntary invitation, provide support information, and avoid academic consequences.", "Follow school policy for minors, guardian permission, assent, storage, and access."), "conclusion" => "The original survey fails voluntariness and privacy protections and should not proceed as designed."),
        array("title" => "Anonymous or confidential?", "scenario" => "A survey stores responses with student IDs in an access-restricted file.", "steps" => array("Researchers can link IDs to students, so the data are not anonymous.", "Restricted access and identity protection are confidentiality measures.", "Store the linkage separately, limit access, define deletion time, and report only groups large enough to protect identity."), "conclusion" => "The survey may be confidential if safeguards work, but it must not be described as anonymous."),
        array("title" => "Misleading rewards graph", "scenario" => "A bar chart compares 94% with 96% using a vertical axis from 93.5% to 96.5% and oversized 3D bars.", "steps" => array("The narrow truncated axis makes a two-point difference fill most of the graph.", "Three-dimensional bars add visual distortion without data value.", "Show the full 0%-100% context or clearly justify a focused scale, label exact values, remove 3D effects, and discuss practical importance."), "conclusion" => "The values may be correct while the visual impression is ethically misleading."),
        array("title" => "Selective product test", "scenario" => "A company measures ten outcomes but advertises only the one that improved.", "steps" => array("Testing many outcomes creates opportunities for a chance improvement.", "Hiding the other nine outcomes is selective reporting.", "Pre-register primary outcomes when possible, report all planned measures, distinguish exploratory analysis, and disclose uncertainty."), "conclusion" => "Selective reporting prevents readers from judging the full evidence."),
    ),
    "misconceptions" => array(
        array("A signature proves informed consent.", "Consent must be understandable, informed, voluntary, and ongoing."),
        array("Confidential and anonymous mean the same.", "Confidential data retain a protected identity link; anonymous data do not reasonably contain one."),
        array("Removing names guarantees anonymity.", "Rare combinations and linked records can re-identify people."),
        array("Large rewards are always ethical.", "A reward can create undue influence when people feel unable to refuse."),
        array("A true graph cannot be misleading.", "Scale, selection, and visual design can distort the impression even when plotted numbers are technically correct."),
        array("Unfavourable results may be discarded.", "Honest research reports planned outcomes and explains deviations rather than hiding inconvenient evidence.")
    ),
    "why" => array("Statistics concerns people even when the spreadsheet contains only numbers. Collection choices affect autonomy, dignity, privacy, opportunity, and trust. Ethical failure can harm participants and make the resulting data less truthful.", "Integrity also protects future decisions. Schools, families, companies, and governments need a complete picture, not a result engineered through selective analysis or a graph designed to win an argument."),
    "knowledge_check" => array(
        stats_classify("kc1", "Researchers retain a protected code that can reconnect responses to names.", $ethicsOptions, "c", "<p>The identities are known through a code but protected, so this is confidentiality rather than anonymity.</p>", "Can researchers reconnect identity?", "foundational", array("confidentiality")),
        stats_classify("kc2", "A survey never collects names, emails, IDs, or identifying combinations.", $ethicsOptions, "d", "<p>Responses are not reasonably linkable to identity, which describes anonymity.</p>", "No identity link exists.", "foundational", array("anonymity")),
        stats_classify("kc3", "A study collects home address even though it is unrelated to the question.", $ethicsOptions, "e", "<p>Collecting unnecessary personal information violates data minimization.</p>", "Is the field needed?", "foundational", array("data minimization"))
    ),
    "guided_practice" => array(
        stats_written("g1", "short-response", "List four elements participants should understand before consenting.", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> Purpose, procedures, foreseeable risks, possible benefits, data use, voluntariness, privacy protections, contacts, and withdrawal rights are valid elements; any four with explanation suffice.</p>", "What would you need to decide freely?", "foundational", array("consent")),
        stats_written("g2", "short-response", "Explain assent when research includes minors.", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> Assent is the minor's affirmative age-appropriate agreement. It is usually considered alongside required parent or guardian permission and does not mean adults can ignore the young person's refusal.</p>", "The minor also has a voice.", "proficient", array("assent")),
        stats_written("g3", "short-response", "Why might a very large payment weaken voluntariness?", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> People with financial need may feel they cannot reasonably refuse despite discomfort or risk. Compensation should recognize time without functioning as coercive pressure.</p>", "Ability to say no matters.", "proficient", array("voluntary participation")),
        stats_classify("g4", "After deception, researchers explain the true purpose and answer questions.", $ethicsOptions, "f", "<p>This post-study explanation is debriefing.</p>", "It occurs after participation.", "foundational", array("debriefing")),
        stats_classify("g5", "A researcher invents 20 missing observations.", $ethicsOptions, "g", "<p>Inventing data is fabrication, a serious research-integrity violation.</p>", "The data never existed.", "foundational", array("integrity")),
        stats_written("g6", "error-analysis", "A team calls an email-collected survey anonymous. Correct the description.", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> Email links responses to identity, so the survey is not anonymous. It may be confidential if the link is protected and access is restricted.</p>", "Known but protected versus unknown.", "proficient", array("privacy")),
        stats_written("g7", "short-response", "Identify two ethical problems with a graph that hides unfavourable dates and truncates its axis.", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> Selective dates hide relevant evidence, and the truncated axis may exaggerate remaining differences. Show the full relevant period, label the scale, and explain any focused view.</p>", "Selection and display are separate choices.", "proficient", array("visual ethics")),
        stats_written("g8", "short-response", "What should a fairness audit ask about a training dataset?", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> Ask who is represented or missing, how outcomes were labelled, whether measurement quality differs by group, which errors occur for each group, and who experiences resulting harm.</p>", "Representation, labels, errors, impact.", "advanced", array("fairness"))
    ),
    "independent_practice" => array(
        stats_classify("i1", "Participants receive understandable information and may stop without penalty.", $ethicsOptions, "a", "<p>These are core features of informed voluntary consent.</p>", "Decision before and during participation.", "foundational", array("consent")),
        stats_classify("i2", "Researchers observe through a private account without permission.", $ethicsOptions, "b", "<p>Accessing a setting where people expect control over access raises a privacy problem.</p>", "Appropriateness of access.", "proficient", array("privacy")),
        stats_written("i3", "short-response", "Distinguish fabrication from falsification.", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> Fabrication invents data or observations. Falsification dishonestly alters methods, materials, records, or existing data.</p>", "Create versus manipulate.", "foundational", array("integrity")),
        stats_written("i4", "short-response", "Why is selective reporting harmful even if the shown result is calculated correctly?", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> Readers cannot see the full set of tests and failures, so they may interpret a chance favourable result as strong planned evidence. The selection changes the meaning of the reported result.</p>", "The hidden results affect context.", "proficient", array("integrity")),
        stats_written("i5", "short-response", "Give two protections for a confidential dataset.", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> Separate identity keys, restrict access, encrypt storage, use strong authentication, remove identifiers from analysis files, set retention limits, and securely delete data are acceptable protections.</p>", "Protect access and linkage.", "foundational", array("security")),
        stats_written("i6", "short-response", "When might deception be considered, and what safeguards are required?", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> It may be considered when full disclosure would invalidate an important low-risk question and no adequate alternative exists. It requires independent review, minimal risk, no deception about serious harm, and prompt debriefing.</p>", "Need, risk, review, explanation.", "advanced", array("deception")),
        stats_written("i7", "short-response", "Explain one re-identification risk in a supposedly anonymous school dataset.", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> A rare combination such as exact age, small program, and uncommon condition may identify the only matching student even after names are removed. Combine or suppress rare categories.</p>", "Identity can emerge from combinations.", "advanced", array("anonymity")),
        stats_written("i8", "error-analysis", "A researcher says consent allows collection of every available student record. Explain.", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> Consent does not remove the duty to minimize data. Collect only fields needed for the stated purpose, explain uses, restrict access, and define retention.</p>", "Permission and necessity are distinct.", "proficient", array("data minimization")),
        stats_written("i9", "short-response", "Evaluate an algorithm trained only on highly active app users for use with all students.", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> The dataset underrepresents inactive and possibly less-connected students, so performance and error rates may differ across groups. Evaluate representative data, compare group-level errors, and limit deployment until harms are addressed.</p>", "Training representation affects who is served well.", "advanced", array("fairness")),
        stats_written("i10", "short-response", "Write a short ethics review for a named, mandatory study-habits survey of minors with public results.", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> The design is not voluntary, lacks appropriate assent and guardian-policy review, collects identifiable information, and risks public academic or social harm. Make participation optional without penalty, obtain required permission and assent, minimize fields, separate identifiers, restrict access, report aggregates, explain withdrawal, and obtain school oversight before proceeding.</p>", "Review choice, minors, identity, risk, storage, reporting, oversight.", "advanced", array("ethics review"))
    ),
    "summary" => array("Informed consent requires understandable information, voluntariness, and withdrawal rights.", "Privacy, confidentiality, and anonymity describe different protections.", "Collect only necessary data and protect it throughout its life cycle.", "Deception requires strong justification, minimal risk, review, and debriefing.", "Integrity requires complete honest reporting, fair visualizations, and attention to dataset representation."),
    "exit_ticket" => array(
        stats_written("e1", "short-response", "In one sentence each, define confidentiality and anonymity.", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> Confidentiality means identities are known or linkable but protected. Anonymity means responses are not reasonably linked to identities, including by the research team.</p>", "Known-and-protected versus not linked.", "proficient", array("privacy")),
        stats_written("e2", "short-response", "Name one ethical obligation at collection and one at reporting.", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> At collection, obtain voluntary informed consent and minimize data. At reporting, present all relevant planned outcomes honestly and avoid misleading visual scales.</p>", "Protect participants and protect the truth.", "proficient", array("ethics"))
    )
);
